Create this file:
/etc/audit/rules.d/insider.rules
And paste everything below, exactly as it is:

⭐ 1. Watch critical system accounts files
-w /etc/passwd -p wa -k auth_changes
-w /etc/shadow -p wa -k auth_changes
-w /etc/group  -p wa -k auth_changes

⭐ 2. Watch sudoers file & sudo binary
-w /etc/sudoers -p wa -k sudo_changes
-w /etc/sudoers.d/ -p wa -k sudo_changes
-w /usr/bin/sudo -p x -k sudo_exec

⭐ 3. Watch bash history (user activity tampering)
-w /root/.bash_history -p wa -k bash_history
-w /home -p wa -k home_mods

(You can add this ONLY if you want user-specific:)
-w /home/<your-username>/.bash_history -p wa -k bash_history

⭐ 4. Watch audit logs themselves (log deletion / tampering)
-w /var/log/audit/ -p wa -k audit_logs
-w /var/log/ -p wa -k syslog_logs

⭐ 5. Watch user management commands
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/sbin/useradd -k user_mgmt
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/sbin/usermod -k user_mgmt
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -F path=/usr/sbin/userdel -k user_mgmt

⭐ 6. Watch permission changes (privilege escalation attempts)
-w /etc/ -p wa -k etc_mods

⭐ 7. Watch file attribute changes (attackers modifying file metadata)
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr -S removexattr -k fs_attr

⭐ 8. Watch kernel module loading/removal (stealthy privilege escalation)
-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S init_module -S delete_module -k module_changes

⭐ After saving the file:
sudo augenrules --load
sudo systemctl restart auditd
sudo auditctl -l

❤️ Summary (Beginner-Friendly Explanation)

This file detects:

| Threat                               | Rule             |
| ------------------------------------ | ---------------- |
| Editing passwd/shadow                | `auth_changes`   |
| Editing sudoers                      | `sudo_changes`   |
| Using sudo suspiciously              | `sudo_exec`      |
| Deleting/modifying bash history      | `bash_history`   |
| Creating/deleting Linux users        | `user_mgmt`      |
| Log deletion / clearing tracks       | `audit_logs`     |
| Privilege escalation via chmod/chown | `etc_mods`       |
| Tampering file attributes            | `fs_attr`        |
| Loading malicious kernel modules     | `module_changes` |
